                    <p>Dark, ponderous figures inch across an open field. Occasionally, one lets out an <em>oink</em>.</p><p>Huang Jianxiang can just make out their silhouettes against the gray sky before the crack of dawn. Yet again, a herd of wild boar has come down from the surrounding mountains to wreak havoc on his rice field.</p><p>“Shoo! Go away! Buzz off!” The 70-year-old farmer is shouting at the top of his lungs. The hungry animals eventually get the message, turning tail and fleeing. The boars are a major threat to his rice farm, which sits at the foot of the Wuyi Mountains in the eastern province of Fujian.</p><p>“In summer and fall, they come to sabotage our rice. In winter and spring, they eat our bamboo shoots,” Huang tells Sixth Tone. As summer melts into fall, piglets start coming down the mountain with their mothers. They are a farmer’s worst nightmare.</p><p><div data-mouseover-social="true" class="author-news-block pull-left">
